00:00:20.925 --> 00:00:22.610
PROFESSOR: So today,
the general theme

00:00:22.610 --> 00:00:24.400
is going to be to
try to understand

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:26.910
how bacteria find food.

00:00:26.910 --> 00:00:30.350
And in particular, how do they
know which direction to swim?

00:00:30.350 --> 00:00:31.880
How do they swim
given that they're

00:00:31.880 --> 00:00:34.230
operating in this low
Reynolds number regime

00:00:34.230 --> 00:00:37.770
that you read about
maybe last night?

00:00:37.770 --> 00:00:41.920
What did you guys think of the
life in low Reynolds number?

00:00:41.920 --> 00:00:45.452
Yeah, it's kind of fun.

00:00:45.452 --> 00:00:47.160
You very much get the
impression that you

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:51.460
are kind of there in that
lecture hall with him.

00:00:51.460 --> 00:00:55.111
They do say that some
essential arm waving was not

00:00:55.111 --> 00:00:56.110
reproduced or so, right?

00:00:56.110 --> 00:01:00.189
But you kind of imagine his
arms waving as he talks,

00:01:00.189 --> 00:01:01.980
even though you don't
get to hear him talk.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:06.340
So that's fun.

00:01:06.340 --> 00:01:08.260
And it's a surprising
number of typos

00:01:08.260 --> 00:01:11.347
given that-- every time I
read that, I'm like, somehow

00:01:11.347 --> 00:01:13.430
this is still the best
version that I've been able

00:01:13.430 --> 00:01:16.390
find of that talk.

00:01:16.390 --> 00:01:20.130
But I think it's just
a neat example of how

00:01:20.130 --> 00:01:22.710
clearly a talented physicist
can kind of from a naive

00:01:22.710 --> 00:01:26.270
perspective say interesting
things about the way

00:01:26.270 --> 00:01:28.660
that life has to work.

00:01:28.660 --> 00:01:32.707
Now today, so we will
be talking indeed

00:01:32.707 --> 00:01:34.040
about how bacteria are swimming.

00:01:34.040 --> 00:01:36.160
But we want to
start by just making

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:40.060
sure we understand something
about how diffusion works,

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:42.640
what life is like in this
low Reynolds number regime.

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:46.970
And for these sorts of problems,
it's really very, very valuable

00:01:46.970 --> 00:01:49.230
if you can just apply some
simple dimensional analysis

00:01:49.230 --> 00:01:49.730
ideas.

00:01:49.730 --> 00:01:53.410
And so we're going to practice
that in a few different cases,

00:01:53.410 --> 00:01:57.490
that dimension analysis can
often tell you a great deal.

00:01:57.490 --> 00:02:01.387
In many cases, you can
discover new physical laws.

00:02:01.387 --> 00:02:03.220
You can figure out how
things have to scale.

00:02:03.220 --> 00:02:06.026
And in some cases, the
scalings are rather surprising.

00:02:09.130 --> 00:02:11.400
And given some of
the constraints

00:02:11.400 --> 00:02:15.240
that microscopic life is facing
in this low Reynolds number

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:18.810
regime where diffusion is very
important, viscous forces are

00:02:18.810 --> 00:02:21.130
dominating over these
inertial forces,

00:02:21.130 --> 00:02:24.060
it really constrains what
bacteria, for example,

00:02:24.060 --> 00:02:24.700
are able to do.

00:02:24.700 --> 00:02:27.080
And it really
constrains how they

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:31.630
have to go about solving
the challenges of life.

00:02:31.630 --> 00:02:34.940
So what I want to do
is start by thinking

00:02:34.940 --> 00:02:39.590
about just a very kind of simple
situation, which is we have in,

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:44.310
we'll say water, a
non-permeable membrane that

00:02:44.310 --> 00:02:47.420
is separating two compartments.

00:02:47.420 --> 00:02:52.670
Whereas over here, we have maybe
salt or something on the right.

00:02:52.670 --> 00:02:55.130
So this is a salty solution.

00:03:01.370 --> 00:03:03.575
And this is pure water.

00:03:08.590 --> 00:03:12.590
Now, this is a
non-permeable membrane.

00:03:12.590 --> 00:03:15.506
So it doesn't allow
the salt to cross.

00:03:15.506 --> 00:03:16.880
But the question
is, what happens

00:03:16.880 --> 00:03:21.770
if I puncture, and I put a
little hole in the membrane

00:03:21.770 --> 00:03:25.660
of some radius a, let's say?

00:03:25.660 --> 00:03:32.840
Now, the question is, what will
be the flow rate, the net flow,

00:03:32.840 --> 00:03:36.996
of salt, in this case,
from the right to the left?

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:53.190
All right, so first of all,
can somebody kind of answer

00:03:53.190 --> 00:03:55.670
at least for a couple-- what
are possible things that

00:03:55.670 --> 00:03:58.890
might be relevant if we're
going to try to figure this out?

00:03:58.890 --> 00:04:01.772
What quantities will we
need to know or measure?

00:04:01.772 --> 00:04:02.990
AUDIENCE: Concentration.

00:04:02.990 --> 00:04:04.906
PROFESSOR: Concentration
seems relevant, yeah.

00:04:09.430 --> 00:04:11.850
And in this case, there's
only one concentration.

00:04:11.850 --> 00:04:14.170
Because well, this
conservation is

00:04:14.170 --> 00:04:17.510
0 here, and some
concentration c over here.

00:04:17.510 --> 00:04:19.134
What else might we need to know?

00:04:19.134 --> 00:04:20.649
AUDIENCE: Pore size.

00:04:20.649 --> 00:04:22.390
PROFESSOR: The
pore size, perfect.

00:04:22.390 --> 00:04:25.848
We'll use a as the
radius of the pore.

00:04:31.700 --> 00:04:33.246
And is that going to do it?

00:04:37.070 --> 00:04:38.947
AUDIENCE: You need a
time for something.

00:04:38.947 --> 00:04:40.030
PROFESSOR: We need a time.

00:04:40.030 --> 00:04:45.150
Because what we want is
some number of molecules

00:04:45.150 --> 00:04:48.010
per unit time that is going
to be crossing from the right

00:04:48.010 --> 00:04:48.510
to the left.

00:04:48.510 --> 00:04:51.701
So we need something
that has a time.

00:04:51.701 --> 00:04:52.200
Yes.

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:53.445
AUDIENCE: The diffusivity.

00:04:53.445 --> 00:04:55.060
PROFESSOR: All right,
the diffusivity.

00:04:55.060 --> 00:04:59.390
So D, so we'll say D, which
is the diffusion coefficient.

00:05:04.550 --> 00:05:07.594
How many S's?

00:05:07.594 --> 00:05:15.723
All right, now other things
that might be relevant?

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:21.140
AUDIENCE: Temperature

00:05:21.140 --> 00:05:22.266
PROFESSOR: Temperature, OK.

00:05:22.266 --> 00:05:24.598
AUDIENCE: I guess it's probably
going to be incorporated

00:05:24.598 --> 00:05:25.450
into the [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:25.450 --> 00:05:28.710
PROFESSOR: Exactly, right,
so indeed the flow rate

00:05:28.710 --> 00:05:31.050
will be dependent
upon the temperature.

00:05:31.050 --> 00:05:34.728
But the way that that manifests
is by doing what to D?

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:39.790
In general, if we go up
to higher temperature,

00:05:39.790 --> 00:05:41.512
how will D change?

00:05:41.512 --> 00:05:42.892
AUDIENCE: Should get bigger.

00:05:42.892 --> 00:05:44.350
PROFESSOR: Should
get bigger, yeah,

00:05:44.350 --> 00:05:48.700
so indeed, D will be typically
given by this Einstein

00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:49.840
relation of kT over gamma.

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:52.160
We'll talk more about
this in a little bit.

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:54.537
But for now, let's just
say that D is something

00:05:54.537 --> 00:05:55.370
that we've measured.

00:05:58.650 --> 00:06:02.824
Now, other things that may
enter into the expression?

00:06:07.060 --> 00:06:08.850
All right, so this
is pretty simple.

00:06:08.850 --> 00:06:10.200
We have three things.

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:16.510
Now, the question is, if we
double the size of the pore,

00:06:16.510 --> 00:06:22.770
i.e. if we double a, how
does the flow rate change?

00:06:22.770 --> 00:06:25.690
So we'll go ahead and do a
vote, since we like to do this.

00:06:35.617 --> 00:06:36.700
All right, so we double a.

00:06:36.700 --> 00:06:42.282
The flow goes up by what factor?

00:06:42.282 --> 00:06:44.164
All right, maybe not all.

00:06:58.050 --> 00:07:01.000
All right, and if you
think it's something else,

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:05.500
you can splay your cards out.

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:08.540
Now, the idea here is that
using dimensional analysis,

00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:10.730
we should be able
to figure this out.

00:07:10.730 --> 00:07:16.208
Now, I'll give you just a minute
to try to think through this.

00:07:30.186 --> 00:07:31.665
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:31.665 --> 00:07:33.850
PROFESSOR: All right,
so you don't even

00:07:33.850 --> 00:07:35.568
need to know this in principle.

00:07:35.568 --> 00:07:37.692
I'm going to give you
something else that may help.

00:07:55.881 --> 00:07:56.964
AUDIENCE: Will it be by x?

00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:05.410
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so this is
the mean squared distance

00:08:05.410 --> 00:08:06.825
that something will diffuse.

00:08:10.020 --> 00:08:11.456
So I wasn't
explaining, because I

00:08:11.456 --> 00:08:12.830
was sort of-- a
hint in the sense

00:08:12.830 --> 00:08:14.760
that in case you might
remember something

00:08:14.760 --> 00:08:17.023
like an equation like-- Yes.

00:08:17.023 --> 00:08:20.410
AUDIENCE: Are we doing this
at the very beginning of--

00:08:20.410 --> 00:08:25.446
PROFESSOR: Yes,
right, OK, so there's

00:08:25.446 --> 00:08:27.320
going to be some question
of timescales here.

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:31.180
OK, so it's really that
after you puncture the hole,

00:08:31.180 --> 00:08:34.570
very rapidly it's
going to assume

00:08:34.570 --> 00:08:37.020
some kind of steady state.

00:08:37.020 --> 00:08:40.610
And then the flow rate will be
constant for some rather long

00:08:40.610 --> 00:08:41.270
time.

00:08:41.270 --> 00:08:44.960
But then eventually the
concentration on this half

00:08:44.960 --> 00:08:46.170
will decrease.

00:08:46.170 --> 00:08:48.120
So we're thinking
about the flow rate

00:08:48.120 --> 00:08:50.200
after you've reached
that steady state,

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:55.010
but before you've
equilibrated across the two

00:08:55.010 --> 00:08:57.119
sides of the tube.

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:09.690
All right, do you
need more time?

00:09:09.690 --> 00:09:12.280
All right, let's go ahead
and see where we are.

00:09:12.280 --> 00:09:16.261
Ready-- three, two, one.

00:09:19.560 --> 00:09:24.720
All right, so we have a
pretty good agreement.

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:31.167
It seems that it's D.
But didn't I tell you

00:09:31.167 --> 00:09:32.417
how to do the problem already?

00:09:42.470 --> 00:09:47.250
OK, so it's not--

00:09:47.250 --> 00:09:48.972
AUDIENCE: So the
naive thing, I guess,

00:09:48.972 --> 00:09:52.806
would be C. Because--
oh, sorry, never mind.

00:09:55.310 --> 00:09:58.644
Except for-- [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:58.644 --> 00:10:00.060
PROFESSOR: All
right, so I'm going

00:10:00.060 --> 00:10:04.120
to give you another--
collaborate with a neighbor.

00:10:04.120 --> 00:10:08.540
And I'll tell you that
it's not D to nudge you

00:10:08.540 --> 00:10:11.455
in the right direction.

00:10:11.455 --> 00:10:13.965
So spend a minute.

00:10:13.965 --> 00:10:16.790
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:11:17.830 --> 00:11:20.105
PROFESSOR: All right, let's
go ahead and reconvene.

00:11:23.637 --> 00:11:25.710
All right, I just want
to see where we are now.

00:11:25.710 --> 00:11:29.350
So if you still believe it's
D despite my telling you

00:11:29.350 --> 00:11:31.370
that I don't think it's
D, you can still vote D,

00:11:31.370 --> 00:11:32.260
and then we can argue about it.

00:11:32.260 --> 00:11:33.135
And that's fine, too.

00:11:33.135 --> 00:11:35.400
All right, ready--
three, two, one.

00:11:39.400 --> 00:11:43.650
OK, so now there's maybe a
disagreement between A and C

00:11:43.650 --> 00:11:44.420
now.

00:11:44.420 --> 00:11:47.418
All right, well,
nobody liked my root 2?

00:11:50.110 --> 00:11:52.540
Maybe you saw me hesitate a
little bit before I wrote it.

00:11:52.540 --> 00:11:55.670
I was like, oh, let
me throw in a root.

00:11:55.670 --> 00:12:03.750
So indeed the flow rate
does not scale as the area.

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:07.600
It only scales with a linear
dimension of this hole.

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:11.264
This is weird, which is
why everybody says D.

00:12:11.264 --> 00:12:12.930
And even after you've
done this problem,

00:12:12.930 --> 00:12:15.320
you still think it's
D in your intuition.

00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:17.780
But you have to like pound
that intuition away from you.

00:12:17.780 --> 00:12:20.230
We'll try to understand
in multiple different ways

00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:21.262
why this might be.

00:12:21.262 --> 00:12:22.720
But what I want to
do first is just

00:12:22.720 --> 00:12:25.460
make sure that we understand
from dimensional analysis

00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:28.970
why this has to be the case.

00:12:28.970 --> 00:12:31.730
Now, the first thing you need
to know for dimensional analysis

00:12:31.730 --> 00:12:34.520
is the units of your answer.

00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:36.120
We're looking for
something that is

00:12:36.120 --> 00:12:40.100
going to be units, some
number of molecules over time.

00:12:40.100 --> 00:12:42.080
Number-- there's no
units attached to that.

00:12:42.080 --> 00:12:45.400
So the answer is supposed
to be just 1 over time.

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:47.210
Indeed, this is why
we needed something

00:12:47.210 --> 00:12:49.390
that had some unit
of time somewhere

00:12:49.390 --> 00:12:52.660
in order to get an answer
that could possibly do this.

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:55.370
And indeed, we know that
the diffusion coefficient

00:12:55.370 --> 00:12:59.130
has units of, for example,
microns squared per second.

00:12:59.130 --> 00:13:01.860
So it's a length
squared over time.

00:13:01.860 --> 00:13:04.942
Now, the one barrier
that people have

00:13:04.942 --> 00:13:06.650
to use dimensional
analysis is because we

00:13:06.650 --> 00:13:09.760
have trouble remembering
what the units of things are.

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:12.030
So if you don't
remember something

00:13:12.030 --> 00:13:13.780
like the units of a
diffusion coefficient,

00:13:13.780 --> 00:13:18.010
then what you have to do is
try to find some equation

00:13:18.010 --> 00:13:22.100
in your brain where
that symbol is used.

00:13:22.100 --> 00:13:26.980
And of course it should be
the correct use of the symbol.

00:13:26.980 --> 00:13:29.590
So here this is
why I'm saying it.

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:31.160
This is essentially
the definition

00:13:31.160 --> 00:13:34.020
of this linear
diffusion coefficient.

00:13:34.020 --> 00:13:37.200
And from that,
you get the units.

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:39.460
This is just very, very common.

00:13:39.460 --> 00:13:43.150
Something like viscosity,
impossible to remember what

00:13:43.150 --> 00:13:44.390
the units of that thing are.

00:13:44.390 --> 00:13:46.550
But then you just have
equations in your brain

00:13:46.550 --> 00:13:48.800
where the viscosity enters,
and you can figure it out.

00:13:53.190 --> 00:13:54.980
All right, so then
if you want to use

00:13:54.980 --> 00:13:57.425
this dimensional analysis
study, just be very clear.

00:13:57.425 --> 00:13:59.050
Write down what all
the dimensions are.

00:13:59.050 --> 00:14:02.690
And then the answer just
comes screaming out at you

00:14:02.690 --> 00:14:04.030
in general.

00:14:04.030 --> 00:14:07.100
Now, we see that we want
something 1 over time.

00:14:07.100 --> 00:14:08.790
There's only one
of these symbols

00:14:08.790 --> 00:14:10.050
that has a time in there.

00:14:10.050 --> 00:14:12.050
So we know exactly how
the diffusion coefficient

00:14:12.050 --> 00:14:13.710
has to enter.

00:14:13.710 --> 00:14:17.220
We know that the
flow is going to have

00:14:17.220 --> 00:14:20.580
to be something
where we know that D

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:22.339
has to enter in there linearly.

00:14:22.339 --> 00:14:23.880
Because if it was
any other way, then

00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:25.910
the time would have
some weird units.

00:14:25.910 --> 00:14:27.875
It would be time
squared or square root

00:14:27.875 --> 00:14:30.020
of time or something.

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:36.480
Now, it's true that we
could in principle dream up

00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:44.300
something crazy between
concentration and the pore size

00:14:44.300 --> 00:14:47.110
in the sense that
if we wanted to,

00:14:47.110 --> 00:14:58.140
we could do c times-- we could
always add a c times a cubed

00:14:58.140 --> 00:14:59.310
or something like that.

00:14:59.310 --> 00:15:01.790
But of course this is diffusion.

00:15:01.790 --> 00:15:06.100
What that means is that these
are non-interacting diffusing

00:15:06.100 --> 00:15:06.660
molecules.

00:15:06.660 --> 00:15:09.690
That means that if we double
the number of the molecules

00:15:09.690 --> 00:15:11.190
over on the right
hand side, we have

00:15:11.190 --> 00:15:15.580
to double the flow rate in
this diffusion equation.

00:15:15.580 --> 00:15:17.266
And for diffusion,
these molecules

00:15:17.266 --> 00:15:18.390
are not interacting at all.

00:15:18.390 --> 00:15:19.820
They don't see each other.

00:15:19.820 --> 00:15:21.945
And that means if you just
double the concentration

00:15:21.945 --> 00:15:25.360
on the right, you have
to double the flow rate.

00:15:25.360 --> 00:15:30.180
So that means we know that it
has to show up as a single c.

00:15:30.180 --> 00:15:33.620
And all we're left with is
going to be one unit of length

00:15:33.620 --> 00:15:37.390
that we have to get rid of.

00:15:37.390 --> 00:15:43.540
Now, this is not, of course,
a rigorous definition.

00:15:43.540 --> 00:15:47.200
And does this have to be
actually an equal sign?

00:15:47.200 --> 00:15:49.219
No, so what we can
actually say is that it

00:15:49.219 --> 00:15:50.510
has to be proportional to this.

00:15:56.680 --> 00:15:59.050
But actually just from
dimensional analysis

00:15:59.050 --> 00:16:00.640
and this idea of,
say, superposition

00:16:00.640 --> 00:16:03.050
of the concentrations,
you can get

00:16:03.050 --> 00:16:05.830
something that's really kind
of a deep statement about how

00:16:05.830 --> 00:16:08.110
diffusion is going to operate.

00:16:08.110 --> 00:16:09.531
Yes.

00:16:09.531 --> 00:16:11.530
AUDIENCE: It seems to me
that we can break that.

00:16:11.530 --> 00:16:13.093
There's this degeneracy.

00:16:13.093 --> 00:16:15.820
We can't quite sort out the
powers of c and a, right?

00:16:15.820 --> 00:16:18.280
PROFESSOR: Right, so that's
what I was saying, that just

00:16:18.280 --> 00:16:23.130
from the units alone, we could
always add a c times a cubed,

00:16:23.130 --> 00:16:25.550
or to some power.

00:16:25.550 --> 00:16:27.790
And that's why I'm
saying that you

00:16:27.790 --> 00:16:31.540
have to be able to invoke
this idea that if you

00:16:31.540 --> 00:16:34.084
double the concentration
of the salt on the right,

00:16:34.084 --> 00:16:35.250
you'll double the flow rate.

00:16:35.250 --> 00:16:38.060
Because these are
non-interacting molecules.

00:16:38.060 --> 00:16:40.586
Because they're just
diffusing around in solution.

00:16:40.586 --> 00:16:43.574
AUDIENCE: I was going
to say that if we simply

00:16:43.574 --> 00:16:49.052
chose the measure of flow in
90 units of number of atoms,

00:16:49.052 --> 00:16:51.991
but in units of
mass per unit time,

00:16:51.991 --> 00:16:54.032
and concentration in units
of mass per unit time,

00:16:54.032 --> 00:17:00.008
then we would clearly see
what power of c it would be.

00:17:00.008 --> 00:17:02.498
And it would have to be 1.

00:17:05.510 --> 00:17:07.220
PROFESSOR: It's an
interesting-- I think

00:17:07.220 --> 00:17:08.511
I'm going to disagree with you.

00:17:08.511 --> 00:17:15.170
But I want to make sure
that I-- so you want to say,

00:17:15.170 --> 00:17:16.410
OK, you're entering.

00:17:16.410 --> 00:17:21.399
Yeah, the diffusion
coefficient is about what

00:17:21.399 --> 00:17:22.710
the molecule is doing.

00:17:22.710 --> 00:17:26.400
So I'm not sure how we're
going to-- if we measure

00:17:26.400 --> 00:17:29.130
concentration in units
of, you're saying,

00:17:29.130 --> 00:17:33.560
mgs per mil of some protein, or
so, then you're really saying

00:17:33.560 --> 00:17:34.890
that there's some mass density.

00:17:38.020 --> 00:17:44.480
And I guess you can always
define diffusion coefficient,

00:17:44.480 --> 00:17:48.310
even from the standpoint
of-- because we don't even

00:17:48.310 --> 00:17:49.570
need numbers.

00:17:49.570 --> 00:17:53.750
We can measure some
fluorescence or something

00:17:53.750 --> 00:17:54.850
of how it diffuses across.

00:17:54.850 --> 00:17:56.995
So that doesn't require numbers.

00:17:56.995 --> 00:17:58.370
Yeah, I'm trying
to think if this

00:17:58.370 --> 00:18:00.600
is going to end up being
different from the argument.

00:18:03.710 --> 00:18:06.368
I'd have to--

00:18:06.368 --> 00:18:08.422
AUDIENCE: If we put in
the number of molecules,

00:18:08.422 --> 00:18:10.880
then it's going to have to be
number of molecules per time.

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:13.370
And then c has to be linear.

00:18:13.370 --> 00:18:18.780
Because c is number of
molecules per something, right?

00:18:18.780 --> 00:18:24.770
PROFESSOR: OK, yeah, you could,
say, treat molecules as a unit.

00:18:24.770 --> 00:18:28.457
And then that also ends up
requiring that it's-- yeah, no,

00:18:28.457 --> 00:18:29.290
I think that's fair.

00:18:32.360 --> 00:18:34.750
But I'd have to think about
this, how it would play out

00:18:34.750 --> 00:18:37.333
if you try to measure things in
terms of mass per unit volume.

00:18:40.990 --> 00:18:44.139
Of course, you should be able
to calculate this explicitly,

00:18:44.139 --> 00:18:46.680
and then also to figure out what
the proportionality constant

00:18:46.680 --> 00:18:47.179
is.

00:18:47.179 --> 00:18:50.130
But indeed, what you find
is that it scales linearly

00:18:50.130 --> 00:18:52.429
with the radius instead
of as the area, which is,

00:18:52.429 --> 00:18:53.470
I think, very surprising.

00:18:53.470 --> 00:18:55.320
Yes.

00:18:55.320 --> 00:18:59.422
AUDIENCE: We can also say D
scales with a squared times

00:18:59.422 --> 00:18:59.922
flow.

00:19:20.290 --> 00:19:23.160
PROFESSOR: Oh, you're saying
that maybe the concentration is

00:19:23.160 --> 00:19:25.760
not relevant.

00:19:25.760 --> 00:19:30.080
AUDIENCE: If we look at it
that way, then the answer is D.

00:19:30.080 --> 00:19:33.730
PROFESSOR: OK,
what you're saying

00:19:33.730 --> 00:19:37.899
is that maybe somehow
the flow is just equal

00:19:37.899 --> 00:19:38.690
to or proportional.

00:19:38.690 --> 00:19:41.530
It goes as D times a
squared in the sense

00:19:41.530 --> 00:19:42.610
that you would say that--

00:19:42.610 --> 00:19:43.800
AUDIENCE: Over.

00:19:43.800 --> 00:19:44.300
Over.

00:19:49.530 --> 00:19:54.698
PROFESSOR: Right, I think that
this non-interacting particle

00:19:54.698 --> 00:19:56.656
business really does tell
you that the flow has

00:19:56.656 --> 00:19:58.960
to be proportional
to the concentration.

00:19:58.960 --> 00:20:03.970
And yeah, I think that
is sufficient already.

00:20:03.970 --> 00:20:06.410
I agree that just from
units, you could do this.

00:20:06.410 --> 00:20:12.180
But I think, well, it's not
true, and it's nonsensical.

00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:14.226
And it's not proportional to c.

00:20:18.680 --> 00:20:21.160
Let's move on.

00:20:21.160 --> 00:20:24.447
But I think it's
important that it's

00:20:24.447 --> 00:20:26.280
possible to say something
that's a deep kind

00:20:26.280 --> 00:20:31.050
of physical principle just
based on analysis of the units.

00:20:31.050 --> 00:20:32.580
And then, of
course, can somebody

00:20:32.580 --> 00:20:35.310
offer the intuitive explanation
for why this might be?

00:20:35.310 --> 00:20:39.168
Why is it that it goes as
a instead of a squared?

00:20:44.090 --> 00:20:47.830
And this is a little bit weird
given the fact that we all

00:20:47.830 --> 00:20:49.895
check our intuition,
we all say D.

00:20:49.895 --> 00:20:51.770
But the thing is, once
you know an answer,

00:20:51.770 --> 00:20:54.240
you should still try to figure
out what the intuition might

00:20:54.240 --> 00:21:10.180
have been that you missed when
you originally said D. Yes.

00:21:10.180 --> 00:21:12.620
AUDIENCE: OK, this might
not make any sense.

00:21:12.620 --> 00:21:16.583
So say you would first think
it goes like a squared,

00:21:16.583 --> 00:21:18.124
because the area
goes like a squared.

00:21:18.124 --> 00:21:21.575
But then maybe the fact that
the perimeter grows like a,

00:21:21.575 --> 00:21:24.533
and the perimeter
adds drag, maybe that

00:21:24.533 --> 00:21:28.491
would subtract from
or cancel out any--

00:21:28.491 --> 00:21:30.800
not necessarily make sense?

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:37.030
PROFESSOR: Yeah, well, OK,
so I don't think that's

00:21:37.030 --> 00:21:39.087
the intuition that I would use.

00:21:39.087 --> 00:21:41.420
But then we have to figure
out, OK, what might be wrong?

00:21:41.420 --> 00:21:43.520
Well first, I don't think
you can subtract an a.

00:21:43.520 --> 00:21:48.840
But also we haven't invoked
any actual drag in the sense

00:21:48.840 --> 00:21:52.230
that there's no sense that the
perimeter should be-- right?

00:21:57.992 --> 00:21:59.450
All right, so this
is so mysterious

00:21:59.450 --> 00:22:02.910
that we are-- that's fine.

00:22:02.910 --> 00:22:06.130
So the way that I like
to think about this

00:22:06.130 --> 00:22:11.732
is that it's not that
we're shooting bullets

00:22:11.732 --> 00:22:12.440
at this membrane.

00:22:12.440 --> 00:22:15.100
If we were shooting
bullets, or if these

00:22:15.100 --> 00:22:16.820
were raindrops
coming, then indeed

00:22:16.820 --> 00:22:19.470
it would scale as the area.

00:22:19.470 --> 00:22:22.060
But because it's
diffusion, diffusion

00:22:22.060 --> 00:22:27.500
operates on gradients
of concentration.

00:22:27.500 --> 00:22:29.380
And what's happening
here is that you

00:22:29.380 --> 00:22:34.780
get a local depletion of the
concentration at the pore.

00:22:34.780 --> 00:22:37.699
So it's not the case that
you have concentration

00:22:37.699 --> 00:22:39.740
c all the way until you
get to the pore, and then

00:22:39.740 --> 00:22:42.190
all of a sudden you have
a linear gradient of c

00:22:42.190 --> 00:22:44.350
across that little pore,
but rather that you

00:22:44.350 --> 00:22:46.590
have a depletion of
the concentration

00:22:46.590 --> 00:22:49.510
as you approach the pore.

00:22:49.510 --> 00:22:52.070
And so as you grow
the pore, you're

00:22:52.070 --> 00:22:53.450
somehow competing with yourself.

00:22:56.540 --> 00:23:00.110
Another way to
think about this is

00:23:00.110 --> 00:23:02.151
to think about what happens
if we have two pores.

00:23:06.850 --> 00:23:08.560
For example, let's
imagine that we

00:23:08.560 --> 00:23:10.320
have this poor here of size a.

00:23:10.320 --> 00:23:15.430
But now I'm going to add a
second pore over here far away,

00:23:15.430 --> 00:23:15.960
same size.

00:23:18.680 --> 00:23:27.004
What should this do to the
total flow rate, A, B, C, D, E?

00:23:27.004 --> 00:23:29.170
I'll give you 10 seconds
to come up with an opinion.

00:23:31.720 --> 00:23:34.128
So I'm adding a
second pore far away.

00:23:37.720 --> 00:23:39.830
Ready?

00:23:39.830 --> 00:23:47.470
Three, two, one-- all right,
so we're all agreeing.

00:23:47.470 --> 00:23:51.850
And this should be 2x, again.

00:23:51.850 --> 00:23:55.820
This is for two pores now.

00:23:55.820 --> 00:23:57.240
We also get 2x.

00:23:57.240 --> 00:24:01.630
This is because if the two pores
are far away from each other,

00:24:01.630 --> 00:24:04.370
as relative to the
size of the pores,

00:24:04.370 --> 00:24:07.610
then these are really
non-interacting in the sense

00:24:07.610 --> 00:24:11.182
that there's none of
this depletion effect

00:24:11.182 --> 00:24:12.390
that I was telling you about.

00:24:12.390 --> 00:24:15.950
Whereas as we bring
these pores together,

00:24:15.950 --> 00:24:19.010
then they start interfering
with each other.

00:24:19.010 --> 00:24:22.580
Because they each involve
some local depletion

00:24:22.580 --> 00:24:23.560
of the concentration.

00:24:23.560 --> 00:24:27.290
And once that kind of depletion
area starts to overlap,

00:24:27.290 --> 00:24:29.540
then the point is that
there is some molecule that

00:24:29.540 --> 00:24:30.640
was diffusing.

00:24:30.640 --> 00:24:34.700
And if you have the pores
right next to each other,

00:24:34.700 --> 00:24:37.010
you're not going to
get twice the net flow.

00:24:37.010 --> 00:24:38.660
Because that molecule,
it might have

00:24:38.660 --> 00:24:43.854
diffused through the other
pore even if it-- if one pore

00:24:43.854 --> 00:24:45.645
were not there, then
it might have diffused

00:24:45.645 --> 00:24:46.603
through the other pore.

00:24:50.296 --> 00:24:51.670
AUDIENCE: Can you
not think of it

00:24:51.670 --> 00:24:55.630
as having to do with the fact
that under a random walk,

00:24:55.630 --> 00:24:58.105
the displacement goes like
square root of the time?

00:24:58.105 --> 00:25:05.990
So if you increase the
number of molecules

00:25:05.990 --> 00:25:08.715
going through by the
square of the perimeter,

00:25:08.715 --> 00:25:12.060
then actually be like
total molecule displacement

00:25:12.060 --> 00:25:17.300
through [INAUDIBLE]
will only go linearly

00:25:17.300 --> 00:25:20.390
in that perimeter, which
would account for the fact

00:25:20.390 --> 00:25:22.680
that molecule is
coming back across.

00:25:22.680 --> 00:25:24.170
PROFESSOR: Right, so it's true
that the molecules coming back

00:25:24.170 --> 00:25:25.753
across you always
have to worry about.

00:25:25.753 --> 00:25:34.740
But I don't see this
argument actually necessarily

00:25:34.740 --> 00:25:35.793
in my work.

00:25:35.793 --> 00:25:37.793
AUDIENCE: Maybe in the
case of, like [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:37.793 --> 00:25:38.740
which doubled in size.

00:25:38.740 --> 00:25:40.240
PROFESSOR: Oh, I see.

00:25:40.240 --> 00:25:44.065
Yeah, I think that
it may be connected,

00:25:44.065 --> 00:25:47.220
although I'm not sure if
I'm sold on the argument.

00:25:54.170 --> 00:25:56.255
Yeah, I think it's a
little bit dangerous.

00:25:59.300 --> 00:25:59.950
Yeah.

00:25:59.950 --> 00:26:01.516
AUDIENCE: So you
mentioned you appeal

00:26:01.516 --> 00:26:03.240
to some sort of
depletion with that.

00:26:03.240 --> 00:26:07.220
But if you just
punctured a hole in the--

00:26:07.220 --> 00:26:09.530
PROFESSOR: OK, and
this is why there

00:26:09.530 --> 00:26:11.210
is this question of timescale.

00:26:11.210 --> 00:26:12.970
Immediately after you
puncture the hole,

00:26:12.970 --> 00:26:16.110
then the flow rate
will actually be

00:26:16.110 --> 00:26:18.494
higher than it will be
at that steady state.

00:26:18.494 --> 00:26:21.830
AUDIENCE: So it's
going to be a squared.

00:26:21.830 --> 00:26:25.790
PROFESSOR: Yeah, right, I think
that the flow right after you

00:26:25.790 --> 00:26:29.060
puncture it indeed will
scale as a squared.

00:26:29.060 --> 00:26:30.840
Because what you're
doing is you're

00:26:30.840 --> 00:26:34.020
taking the number of
molecules across this area.

00:26:34.020 --> 00:26:36.730
And half of them are
going to come through.

00:26:36.730 --> 00:26:39.225
And there's just more
molecules in that area

00:26:39.225 --> 00:26:40.350
when you first puncture it.

00:26:40.350 --> 00:26:45.532
But that's going to equilibrate
in, whatever, a microsecond.

00:26:45.532 --> 00:26:46.490
That'll be really fast.

00:26:46.490 --> 00:26:49.650
Whereas in the steady
state flow rate,

00:26:49.650 --> 00:26:52.020
that could go in
principle forever

00:26:52.020 --> 00:26:53.445
if it's a large reservoir.

00:26:57.310 --> 00:27:00.210
OK, so I want to move on.

00:27:00.210 --> 00:27:03.640
But I want to make
sure that we understand

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:06.150
how this basic
principle allows us

00:27:06.150 --> 00:27:07.930
to say some interesting things.

00:27:07.930 --> 00:27:10.380
For example, there's
a related problem,

00:27:10.380 --> 00:27:15.468
which is, how much food
could a cell possibly eat?

00:27:19.750 --> 00:27:23.410
And can somebody
say why there might

00:27:23.410 --> 00:27:25.800
be an upper bound on this?

00:27:34.572 --> 00:27:35.988
AUDIENCE: There's
a point at which

00:27:35.988 --> 00:27:38.225
you get too many nutrients
inside of the cell.

00:27:38.225 --> 00:27:39.219
PROFESSOR: I'm sorry?

00:27:39.219 --> 00:27:40.875
AUDIENCE: There's
a point at which

00:27:40.875 --> 00:27:43.700
you get too many nutrients
inside of the cell.

00:27:43.700 --> 00:27:46.930
PROFESSOR: Oh no, this
is a super hungry cell.

00:27:46.930 --> 00:27:53.240
It can in principle be able to
use every glucose molecule that

00:27:53.240 --> 00:27:54.292
came in.

00:27:54.292 --> 00:27:56.690
AUDIENCE: No, but I'm
saying that the osmosis

00:27:56.690 --> 00:28:00.170
of the water coming in
would pop the membrane.

00:28:00.170 --> 00:28:03.150
PROFESSOR: Oh, OK, we're
talking about osmotic effects.

00:28:03.150 --> 00:28:08.630
OK, yeah, but we can
just say that it's

00:28:08.630 --> 00:28:10.500
got a super tough cell wall.

00:28:10.500 --> 00:28:14.486
So it can take,
we'll say, infinite.

00:28:14.486 --> 00:28:16.360
I guess what I'm saying
is there's something.

00:28:16.360 --> 00:28:19.840
Even if I invoke such a
thing, there still is a limit.

00:28:19.840 --> 00:28:22.770
That's really what
I'm trying to say.

00:28:22.770 --> 00:28:25.356
AUDIENCE: The concentration
of the glucose inside the cell

00:28:25.356 --> 00:28:27.900
is a bit high.

00:28:27.900 --> 00:28:30.150
PROFESSOR: Well, the glucose
is going to get imported.

00:28:30.150 --> 00:28:32.150
And then it's going to
