00:28:32.150 --> 00:28:35.060
into useful things.

00:28:35.060 --> 00:28:36.580
But then still there's a limit.

00:28:36.580 --> 00:28:37.513
There's a maximum.

00:28:42.190 --> 00:28:45.168
This is the maximum kind of
possible nutrient uptake.

00:28:48.380 --> 00:28:50.870
Yes.

00:28:50.870 --> 00:28:53.120
AUDIENCE: If the diffusion
is somewhat slow,

00:28:53.120 --> 00:28:56.110
or maybe there's
[INAUDIBLE] around the cell.

00:28:56.110 --> 00:28:59.240
PROFESSOR: OK,
right, so maybe it

00:28:59.240 --> 00:29:02.370
could be somehow
diffusion limited.

00:29:02.370 --> 00:29:05.120
And what's the best that
a cell could possibly

00:29:05.120 --> 00:29:07.390
do in this regard?

00:29:07.390 --> 00:29:09.920
So here's a cell.

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:14.810
And now maybe we will,
again, have it be radius a.

00:29:14.810 --> 00:29:16.200
So this is the cell of radius a.

00:29:20.630 --> 00:29:23.066
The best they can be,
how would you describe

00:29:23.066 --> 00:29:24.190
that relative to diffusion?

00:29:34.769 --> 00:29:38.203
AUDIENCE: Can you
be more specific?

00:29:38.203 --> 00:29:40.167
AUDIENCE: Everything
that [INAUDIBLE] membrane

00:29:40.167 --> 00:29:41.360
could be absorbed.

00:29:41.360 --> 00:29:42.360
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:29:42.360 --> 00:29:45.630
So that's what I was-- so the
best that it could possibly be

00:29:45.630 --> 00:29:47.995
is a perfect absorber.

00:29:47.995 --> 00:29:49.370
What we mean by
that is something

00:29:49.370 --> 00:29:54.153
where the moment that a molecule
touches it, it gets imported.

00:29:59.210 --> 00:30:01.510
Now of course, a cell is
not a perfect absorber.

00:30:01.510 --> 00:30:06.110
But what's fascinating
is that even if it were,

00:30:06.110 --> 00:30:08.860
then it does not
mean that it's going

00:30:08.860 --> 00:30:12.286
to be consuming, say,
glucose at an infinite rate.

00:30:16.102 --> 00:30:17.920
And particularly,
we can ask, well,

00:30:17.920 --> 00:30:19.720
if we have a situation
like this where

00:30:19.720 --> 00:30:24.460
we have a cell, a sphere of
size a, it's a perfect absorber,

00:30:24.460 --> 00:30:29.012
how will its uptake rate
scale with its size?

00:30:36.290 --> 00:30:39.210
In particular, if
we double a, what

00:30:39.210 --> 00:30:41.400
is it going to do for the flow?

00:30:41.400 --> 00:30:44.212
All right, we're going to have
10 seconds to think about this.

00:30:50.150 --> 00:30:52.590
If we imagine a cell as a
perfect absorber, the moment

00:30:52.590 --> 00:30:56.710
that this nutrient touches it,
it gets imported and chewed up.

00:30:56.710 --> 00:31:00.270
The question is, how does
that maximum uptake rate

00:31:00.270 --> 00:31:05.909
change if I double the size of
the cell, double the radius?

00:31:05.909 --> 00:31:06.450
Are we ready?

00:31:09.390 --> 00:31:10.515
OK, let's see where we are.

00:31:10.515 --> 00:31:11.015
Ready?

00:31:11.015 --> 00:31:14.700
Three, two, one.

00:31:14.700 --> 00:31:20.820
OK, so now it's a bit more of
a mixture of A's, C's, D's,

00:31:20.820 --> 00:31:22.350
although it is a majority.

00:31:22.350 --> 00:31:28.900
We're getting a majority
C. And again, this

00:31:28.900 --> 00:31:32.250
is, cell doubles size.

00:31:32.250 --> 00:31:37.020
And indeed, from the standpoint
of dimensional analysis,

00:31:37.020 --> 00:31:42.230
this is the same problem as
that pore that we just did.

00:31:42.230 --> 00:31:45.436
Because again, it's diffusion.

00:31:45.436 --> 00:31:46.569
We're interested in uptake.

00:31:46.569 --> 00:31:48.110
Now, it's not flow
across a membrane.

00:31:48.110 --> 00:31:50.370
But this is uptake
rate by the cell.

00:31:50.370 --> 00:31:53.100
It's going to be numbers
of molecules per unit time.

00:31:53.100 --> 00:31:54.880
Again, there's diffusion.

00:31:54.880 --> 00:31:58.440
The concentration
is still relevant.

00:31:58.440 --> 00:32:01.880
And so all the same
arguments apply.

00:32:01.880 --> 00:32:10.900
And indeed, this is, again,
proportional to the radius a.

00:32:10.900 --> 00:32:17.590
And remember, we're following
the convention of Purcell

00:32:17.590 --> 00:32:18.610
and calling this a.

00:32:18.610 --> 00:32:24.700
Because Reynolds numbers is
an r, and then problems arise.

00:32:24.700 --> 00:32:28.930
Are there any questions about
why the argument is the same

00:32:28.930 --> 00:32:29.935
here as it was there?

00:32:34.910 --> 00:32:38.230
OK, now, there's something
interesting about this though,

00:32:38.230 --> 00:32:46.350
which is that you can imagine
the fact that this only scales

00:32:46.350 --> 00:32:50.240
as the radius of the cell
tells you that there's

00:32:50.240 --> 00:32:52.490
some sense in
which we're wasting

00:32:52.490 --> 00:32:56.040
an awful lot of
that surface area.

00:32:56.040 --> 00:32:59.040
Because we have this
large surface area.

00:32:59.040 --> 00:33:02.380
But it's not as good
as you would have

00:33:02.380 --> 00:33:03.560
thought it would have been.

00:33:03.560 --> 00:33:06.220
And what that means
is in principle,

00:33:06.220 --> 00:33:10.040
you could have a
smaller fraction

00:33:10.040 --> 00:33:18.020
of the area covered by a bunch
of little pores or transporters

00:33:18.020 --> 00:33:20.010
that are kind of analogous
to this situation

00:33:20.010 --> 00:33:23.050
that we had before with the
