00:33:35.640 --> 00:33:37.400
an amusing calculation
you can do,

00:33:37.400 --> 00:33:42.930
which is you can ask, well, how
is it that the-- this is now

00:33:42.930 --> 00:33:43.650
uptake rate.

00:33:47.780 --> 00:33:50.170
We want to know,
how is it that that

00:33:50.170 --> 00:33:55.110
is going to change as a function
of the fraction of the surface

00:33:55.110 --> 00:33:59.160
area that we have covered
with these transporters,

00:33:59.160 --> 00:34:03.130
with these little perfectly
absorbing patches?

00:34:03.130 --> 00:34:09.090
So we imagine the cell is
1 to 10 microns in size.

00:34:09.090 --> 00:34:11.670
Now we have a bunch
of these little pores

00:34:11.670 --> 00:34:13.130
that we're going to go on.

00:34:13.130 --> 00:34:18.409
And of course, this is
going to saturate somewhere.

00:34:18.409 --> 00:34:20.000
And it's going to saturate.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:22.650
And as it turns out, this
goes as 4 pi D, I think.

00:34:22.650 --> 00:34:24.679
Yeah, so the uptake
rate is actually

00:34:24.679 --> 00:34:31.679
equal to 4 pi cDa for a sphere.

00:34:31.679 --> 00:34:34.580
So this is the part that we
could not have figured out

00:34:34.580 --> 00:34:36.710
from dimensional analysis.

00:34:36.710 --> 00:34:39.340
So indeed, the uptake rate,
once we get up to-- this

00:34:39.340 --> 00:34:40.714
is a fraction that's covered.

00:34:40.714 --> 00:34:46.286
Once that's 1, indeed
it's going to be 4 pi cDa.

00:34:50.510 --> 00:34:56.130
Now, the question is, how
does it behave over here?

00:34:56.130 --> 00:34:58.310
Now, you might have
thought that it would just

00:34:58.310 --> 00:35:02.350
be some line like that.

00:35:02.350 --> 00:35:08.870
It's just the more of these
transporters that you have,

00:35:08.870 --> 00:35:13.985
you just get a linear increase
in your total uptake rate.

00:35:13.985 --> 00:35:16.620
But it turns out
that that's not true.

00:35:16.620 --> 00:35:19.290
Because even at just
having, say, 1%,

00:35:19.290 --> 00:35:25.500
roughly, of the surface
covered by this transporter,

00:35:25.500 --> 00:35:32.441
you can get something like 50%
of the total maximal uptake

00:35:32.441 --> 00:35:32.940
rate.

00:35:32.940 --> 00:35:35.060
And that's because
these guys are not

00:35:35.060 --> 00:35:37.605
competing with each other so
much, because they're far away.

00:35:37.605 --> 00:35:46.195
So this curve really looks
something like-- well, OK?

00:35:52.244 --> 00:35:54.160
Now, this is, I think,
especially interesting.

00:35:54.160 --> 00:35:57.820
Because a cell is not trying
to import just one thing.

00:35:57.820 --> 00:36:00.910
In principle, it's trying to
import many different things.

00:36:00.910 --> 00:36:03.290
So you need carbon sources.

00:36:03.290 --> 00:36:06.190
You need all sorts
of trace metals.

00:36:06.190 --> 00:36:07.247
You need nitrogen.

00:36:07.247 --> 00:36:09.330
So in principle, there are
many, many, many things

00:36:09.330 --> 00:36:11.660
that a cell is trying to
get from the environment.

00:36:11.660 --> 00:36:14.512
And by simply having
different transporters

00:36:14.512 --> 00:36:16.220
specific to different
things-- all right,

00:36:16.220 --> 00:36:19.870
so here are some squares
that uptake something else,

00:36:19.870 --> 00:36:25.530
and little, I don't know,
triangles, whatever.

00:36:25.530 --> 00:36:28.480
So you can have many, many, many
of these different transporters

00:36:28.480 --> 00:36:29.980
on the cell surface.

00:36:29.980 --> 00:36:32.460
And they're each
uptaking their own thing.

00:36:32.460 --> 00:36:34.420
And kind of
surprisingly, you can

00:36:34.420 --> 00:36:39.530
get near optimal uptake rates
of many, many different things.

00:36:43.700 --> 00:36:47.210
I feel that I've lost you.

