00:39:27.101 --> 00:39:27.600
right?

00:39:27.600 --> 00:39:31.330
So the way I would
think about it

00:39:31.330 --> 00:39:34.487
is that you don't
have to cover up

00:39:34.487 --> 00:39:36.070
very much of the
cell surface in order

00:39:36.070 --> 00:39:38.864
to get really good
uptake kinetics.

00:39:48.690 --> 00:39:52.660
Now, these are some, say,
fundamental limits to the way

00:39:52.660 --> 00:39:54.830
that bacteria, for
example, and other cells

00:39:54.830 --> 00:39:57.810
can uptake food and
other nutrients.

00:39:57.810 --> 00:39:59.900
But from the
standpoint of trying

00:39:59.900 --> 00:40:02.110
to find where the
nutrients are better,

00:40:02.110 --> 00:40:04.000
what you need to
be able to do is

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:06.041
you need to be able to
measure the concentration.

00:40:08.190 --> 00:40:12.290
Now, the basic way that you
could, for example, measure

00:40:12.290 --> 00:40:16.280
a concentration of something,
the best that you could do,

00:40:16.280 --> 00:40:19.170
is if you're a
perfect absorber, you

00:40:19.170 --> 00:40:22.180
uptake molecules at this rate.

00:40:22.180 --> 00:40:25.720
And then you count the
number of molecules

00:40:25.720 --> 00:40:29.790
that you uptake
over some time t.

00:40:29.790 --> 00:40:34.170
Indeed, the number that
you uptake over some time t

00:40:34.170 --> 00:40:36.995
will just be given by this.

00:40:44.710 --> 00:40:47.405
What will be the distribution
of these numbers?

00:40:55.480 --> 00:40:58.590
I should just have somewhere
up on the side always

00:40:58.590 --> 00:41:00.410
a bunch of probability
distributions

00:41:00.410 --> 00:41:04.172
that we can vote on.

00:41:04.172 --> 00:41:06.380
But think about it for a
moment, and then we'll vote.

00:41:16.240 --> 00:41:18.230
All right, ready?

00:41:18.230 --> 00:41:22.630
Three, two, one.

00:41:22.630 --> 00:41:24.140
What is going to
be the probability

00:41:24.140 --> 00:41:28.290
distribution of the number
of these things absorbed

00:41:28.290 --> 00:41:29.057
over some time?

00:41:29.057 --> 00:41:30.890
Right, it's going to
be distributed Poisson.

00:41:35.500 --> 00:41:39.290
What is going to be the
distribution of times

00:41:39.290 --> 00:41:44.180
between successive
absorption events?

00:41:44.180 --> 00:41:44.680
Ready?

00:41:44.680 --> 00:41:46.784
Three, two, one.

00:41:50.170 --> 00:41:55.307
All right, yeah, that is going
to end up being exponential.

00:41:55.307 --> 00:41:56.390
And this is all confusing.

00:41:56.390 --> 00:41:57.740
So this is a Poisson process.

00:41:57.740 --> 00:42:01.510
These things are occurring at
random times, at some rate.

00:42:01.510 --> 00:42:04.284
And if you have such a
process that's random,

00:42:04.284 --> 00:42:06.200
and you ask, how many
events over some time t,

00:42:06.200 --> 00:42:10.230
that is the definition
of a Poisson.

00:42:10.230 --> 00:42:15.050
If this is a large number, then
the probability distribution

00:42:15.050 --> 00:42:16.751
is going to look
like something else.

00:42:16.751 --> 00:42:18.000
What is it going to look like?

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:19.555
Ready, three, two, one.

00:42:23.990 --> 00:42:26.410
Most people are
trying to find the D,

00:42:26.410 --> 00:42:30.480
the central limit theorem there.

00:42:30.480 --> 00:42:35.120
What is going to determine the
resolution of that measurement

00:42:35.120 --> 00:42:36.150
that we make?

00:42:41.950 --> 00:42:44.920
So in some ways, what you
would like to know is, well,

00:42:44.920 --> 00:42:47.600
what's the standard
deviation in your measurement

00:42:47.600 --> 00:42:55.590
of the concentration divided
by the concentration?

00:42:55.590 --> 00:42:57.565
So this is maybe
a fractional error

00:42:57.565 --> 00:42:59.273
in your measurement
of the concentration.

00:43:04.840 --> 00:43:08.960
Do you guys
understand why this is

00:43:08.960 --> 00:43:15.590
the error in the measurement?

00:43:22.710 --> 00:43:25.720
Well, this actually will go
as the standard deviation

00:43:25.720 --> 00:43:29.150
in our measurement of the
number divided by the number

00:43:29.150 --> 00:43:30.136
that we measure.

00:43:32.841 --> 00:43:35.216
What's going to be the standard
deviation of this number?

00:43:38.565 --> 00:43:39.642
AUDIENCE: The scale--

00:43:39.642 --> 00:43:40.600
PROFESSOR: What's that?

00:43:40.600 --> 00:43:41.770
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:41.770 --> 00:43:44.110
PROFESSOR: The mean,
yeah, so it's close to--

00:43:44.110 --> 00:43:45.820
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:45.820 --> 00:43:49.780
PROFESSOR: Yeah, it's the
square root of the mean number.

00:43:49.780 --> 00:43:52.120
What that means is that
this thing is going to be

00:43:52.120 --> 00:43:56.510
the square root of a 4 pi cDaT.

00:43:56.510 --> 00:43:58.660
And this is just 4 pi cDaT.

00:44:18.720 --> 00:44:20.950
The number that
you measure here,

00:44:20.950 --> 00:44:22.950
the number that you uptake
over some time period

00:44:22.950 --> 00:44:24.908
t, that's going to be
distributed as a Poisson.

00:44:24.908 --> 00:44:26.340
And in a Poisson,
the variance is

00:44:26.340 --> 00:44:29.380
equal to the mean, which means
the standard deviation, which

00:44:29.380 --> 00:44:32.510
is the square root
of the variance.

00:44:32.510 --> 00:44:33.960
It's going to be this.

00:44:33.960 --> 00:44:34.758
Yes.

00:44:34.758 --> 00:44:36.924
AUDIENCE: I'm not understanding
the first step where

00:44:36.924 --> 00:44:39.080
you changed the c [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:39.080 --> 00:44:45.170
PROFESSOR: Right, so from
