00:49:14.620 --> 00:49:17.686
All right, let's see where we
are-- ready, three, two, one.

00:49:21.310 --> 00:49:25.425
Oh, we have a fair
range of answers.

00:49:25.425 --> 00:49:27.160
All right, I think
everybody agrees

00:49:27.160 --> 00:49:28.480
it's going to do something.

00:49:28.480 --> 00:49:30.340
Because it would be
kind of a coincidence

00:49:30.340 --> 00:49:31.860
if it didn't change things.

00:49:31.860 --> 00:49:35.810
Can I get somebody
to volunteer what

00:49:35.810 --> 00:49:37.260
their neighbor is thinking?

00:49:37.260 --> 00:49:39.468
I know you didn't actually
talk to your neighbor yet.

00:49:39.468 --> 00:49:41.012
But you can still invoke that.

00:49:47.500 --> 00:49:48.370
Yes.

00:49:48.370 --> 00:49:50.350
AUDIENCE: So I don't
know about this so much.

00:49:50.350 --> 00:49:53.132
But the first thing
I was thinking

00:49:53.132 --> 00:49:56.958
is that maybe this monitor
might be encountered on

00:49:56.958 --> 00:50:00.241
at a different rate
proportional to its area.

00:50:03.670 --> 00:50:07.364
It seemed like it wouldn't
change the concentration

00:50:07.364 --> 00:50:09.438
gradient, because it
wouldn't be subtracting any.

00:50:09.438 --> 00:50:11.188
And so then things
would bounce off of it,

00:50:11.188 --> 00:50:13.914
and that would be
proportional to its area.

00:50:13.914 --> 00:50:15.330
PROFESSOR: OK,
that's interesting.

00:50:15.330 --> 00:50:18.240
So you're arguing for
a different scaling.

00:50:18.240 --> 00:50:22.030
And then it would actually be
either-- depending on the area,

00:50:22.030 --> 00:50:23.440
then it would be different.

00:50:23.440 --> 00:50:25.544
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so that
seemed weird to me,

00:50:25.544 --> 00:50:28.002
which is why I wanted to just
check where other people were

00:50:28.002 --> 00:50:29.005
on that.

00:50:29.005 --> 00:50:30.380
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
no, that's fair.

00:50:30.380 --> 00:50:31.210
That's fair.

00:50:31.210 --> 00:50:32.970
In the end, the
scaling is the same.

00:50:32.970 --> 00:50:36.880
Although this is very
complicated, confusing.

00:50:36.880 --> 00:50:39.661
Can I hear somebody else
argue for one or the other?

00:50:39.661 --> 00:50:41.160
Because he actually
argued for both.

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:48.764
AUDIENCE: I just thought if it's
not taking up the molecules,

00:50:48.764 --> 00:50:52.033
then it could bounce against
the same molecule several times.

00:50:52.033 --> 00:50:54.800
PROFESSOR: Yeah, and
therefore, so which

00:50:54.800 --> 00:50:56.110
one are you arguing for?

00:50:56.110 --> 00:50:56.949
AUDIENCE: For worse.

00:50:56.949 --> 00:50:58.240
PROFESSOR: Yeah, for worse, OK.

00:50:58.240 --> 00:51:00.517
Yeah, and indeed, it
does end up being worse.

00:51:00.517 --> 00:51:02.100
And it's actually
significantly worse.

00:51:02.100 --> 00:51:06.060
It's something like
10 times worse.

00:51:06.060 --> 00:51:08.660
And I think the intuitive
explanation is indeed

00:51:08.660 --> 00:51:11.530
what you just said, that a
perfect monitor, that's great.

00:51:11.530 --> 00:51:13.707
Except for the fact that
it's counting every time

00:51:13.707 --> 00:51:14.540
that something hits.

00:51:14.540 --> 00:51:17.640
But then it doesn't know if it
already counted that molecule

00:51:17.640 --> 00:51:18.230
or not.

00:51:18.230 --> 00:51:20.510
So then there's
extra uncertainty

00:51:20.510 --> 00:51:23.180
that results from that.

00:51:23.180 --> 00:51:25.810
Of course, ultimately, you have
to go and do the calculation

00:51:25.810 --> 00:51:27.935
if you want to be convinced
of something like this.

00:51:27.935 --> 00:51:31.200
But indeed, the perfect
absorber is the best

00:51:31.200 --> 00:51:32.430
that you can possibly do.

00:51:37.330 --> 00:51:41.260
AUDIENCE: Unless it tagged
the molecule [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:41.260 --> 00:51:42.270
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:51:42.270 --> 00:51:44.150
Right, so that's equivalent
to being a perfect absorber,

00:51:44.150 --> 00:51:44.650
right?

00:51:44.650 --> 00:51:46.721
AUDIENCE: Oh, OK.

00:51:46.721 --> 00:51:48.729
Well, no, because then-- oh.

00:51:48.729 --> 00:51:51.270
PROFESSOR: Yeah, because these
are non-interacting molecules.

00:51:51.270 --> 00:51:53.270
So if you tag it green,
then all that you

00:51:53.270 --> 00:51:54.820
do is when the green
molecule comes back, you say,

00:51:54.820 --> 00:51:55.950
I'm going to ignore that.

00:51:55.950 --> 00:51:59.480
But then that's equivalent to
if you had just absorbed it.

00:51:59.480 --> 00:52:01.330
AUDIENCE: But there's
no local depletion.

00:52:01.330 --> 00:52:03.740
PROFESSOR: Yeah, there's
no local depletion.

00:52:03.740 --> 00:52:06.620
But because these are all
non-interacting particles,

00:52:06.620 --> 00:52:09.610
then it can't make a difference.

00:52:09.610 --> 00:52:12.290
And I agree that
this is confusing.

00:52:12.290 --> 00:52:15.450
But I'm pretty confident
what I said is true.

00:52:15.450 --> 00:52:17.200
Because since they're
all non-interacting,

00:52:17.200 --> 00:52:19.610
there's just no more
information there.

00:52:19.610 --> 00:52:20.345
Yeah.

00:52:20.345 --> 00:52:25.200
AUDIENCE: So what
exactly is the error?

00:52:25.200 --> 00:52:28.146
PROFESSOR: Right,
OK, this is asking,

00:52:28.146 --> 00:52:30.520
over some period of time, I
count the number of molecules

00:52:30.520 --> 00:52:34.720
that hit me or that I absorb,
and then I say, OK, well, I

00:52:34.720 --> 00:52:37.215
think that I counted 20.

00:52:37.215 --> 00:52:38.590
And the question
is really, well,

00:52:38.590 --> 00:52:44.100
if I did this again, how
close to 20 would I get?

00:52:44.100 --> 00:52:49.820
Would I get, again, 20 or 21, or
would I next time get 10 or 50?

00:52:49.820 --> 00:52:51.510
And that's the real question.

00:52:51.510 --> 00:52:54.640
How repeatable are
my measurements?

00:52:54.640 --> 00:52:58.900
So if I plot a histogram
of a bunch of numbers

00:52:58.900 --> 00:53:07.930
that I get over this time-- this
is the frequency that I observe

00:53:07.930 --> 00:53:11.090
a particular number of molecules
over some period of time t.

00:53:11.090 --> 00:53:12.410
I get some histogram.

00:53:12.410 --> 00:53:14.170
And this is telling us about
the width of that histogram

00:53:14.170 --> 00:53:15.044
relative to the mean.

00:53:21.810 --> 00:53:23.450
Now let's imagine
that you're the cell,

00:53:23.450 --> 00:53:25.900
and you calculated
the concentration

00:53:25.900 --> 00:53:27.840
in a really wonderful way.

00:53:27.840 --> 00:53:30.670
Now, the question
is, do you know where

00:53:30.670 --> 00:53:33.700
you should go to get more food?

00:53:33.700 --> 00:53:34.200
No, right?

00:53:34.200 --> 00:53:36.158
So you know the concentration
at your location.

00:53:36.158 --> 00:53:40.450
But what you need to know for
that purpose is a gradient.

00:53:40.450 --> 00:53:42.920
And I'm trying to
remember, in this paper,

00:53:42.920 --> 00:53:44.980
they maybe are
not very explicit.

00:53:44.980 --> 00:53:48.320
Why is it that a
bacterial cell might

00:53:48.320 --> 00:53:51.400
do this biased random walk
that's described in the paper

00:53:51.400 --> 00:53:53.970
instead of just
measure the gradient?

00:53:56.590 --> 00:53:57.574
Yeah.

00:53:57.574 --> 00:53:58.560
AUDIENCE: Because
cell size is so small.

00:53:58.560 --> 00:54:00.450
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so
bacteria are just small,

00:54:00.450 --> 00:54:03.380
I think this is the
argument that we often give.

00:54:03.380 --> 00:54:07.530
And that's just saying that if
you want to measure a gradient,

00:54:07.530 --> 00:54:10.930
then what you would do is, if
you have a sphere like this,

00:54:10.930 --> 00:54:13.590
you might say, OK,
I'm going to count

00:54:13.590 --> 00:54:16.007
the number of the molecules
that hit me over here,

00:54:16.007 --> 00:54:18.340
and I'm going to compare that
to the number of molecules

00:54:18.340 --> 00:54:20.870
that hit me over there.

00:54:20.870 --> 00:54:23.692
So you get two measurements
of concentration.

00:54:23.692 --> 00:54:26.650
But then in order to get a
gradient, what's relevant

00:54:26.650 --> 00:54:30.630
is you have to look
at this distance.

00:54:30.630 --> 00:54:33.740
And of course if you
have a bigger cell, then

00:54:33.740 --> 00:54:35.810
a given gradient shows
up as a larger difference

00:54:35.810 --> 00:54:37.970
in concentration, or
a large difference

00:54:37.970 --> 00:54:40.430
in the number of molecules
that are going to hit the cell.

00:54:40.430 --> 00:54:44.560
And does that scale linearly
or quadratically with a?

00:54:48.898 --> 00:54:49.870
AUDIENCE: Linearly?

00:54:49.870 --> 00:54:53.540
PROFESSOR: Linearly--
difference in concentration

00:54:53.540 --> 00:54:58.660
is going to be equal to the
size of the cell, maybe 2a,

00:54:58.660 --> 00:55:01.810
times dc/dx.

00:55:01.810 --> 00:55:04.450
So there's some gradient
that's out there.

00:55:04.450 --> 00:55:08.680
And then so we get a linear
amplification of our signal

00:55:08.680 --> 00:55:10.640
based on the size of the cell.

00:55:10.640 --> 00:55:12.860
So if you look at
many eukaryotic cells,

00:55:12.860 --> 00:55:15.930
for example Dicty and
others, they indeed

00:55:15.930 --> 00:55:19.210
often do this direct
gradient measurement.

00:55:19.210 --> 00:55:23.226
And then from that,
they decide where to go.

00:55:23.226 --> 00:55:24.600
Bacteria, on the
other hand, they

00:55:24.600 --> 00:55:28.370
do this other thing that's
described in the paper where

00:55:28.370 --> 00:55:29.800
they have a biased random walk.

00:55:29.800 --> 00:55:32.258
We're going to be talking much
more about this and the gene

00:55:32.258 --> 00:55:34.510
network that allows cells
to do it on Tuesday.

00:55:34.510 --> 00:55:36.380
But the basic idea
is that the bacteria,

00:55:36.380 --> 00:55:39.480
they're swimming in
some random direction.

00:55:39.480 --> 00:55:44.800
And then instead of directly
measuring the concentration

00:55:44.800 --> 00:55:48.860
as dc/dx, which you might
do as a eukaryotic cell,

00:55:48.860 --> 00:55:51.950
instead what they measure is
the change in concentration

00:55:51.950 --> 00:55:53.500
with respect to time.

00:55:53.500 --> 00:55:54.580
Because they are moving.

00:55:54.580 --> 00:55:55.880
So they ask, are
things getting better?

00:55:55.880 --> 00:55:57.060
Are they getting worse?

00:55:57.060 --> 00:55:59.350
If things are getting
better, you keep on going.

00:55:59.350 --> 00:56:00.891
If things are getting
worse, then you

00:56:00.891 --> 00:56:04.120
randomize your direction,
and you try again.

00:56:04.120 --> 00:56:07.460
And this implements
a biased random walk.

00:56:07.460 --> 00:56:10.070
We'll talk about the
decision making circuit

00:56:10.070 --> 00:56:12.730
in the cell that allows
it to do that on Tuesday.

00:56:12.730 --> 00:56:17.260
But that's the
basic notion there.

00:56:17.260 --> 00:56:19.350
And can someone
remind us, how long

00:56:19.350 --> 00:56:22.636
is a typical run for E. coli?

00:56:22.636 --> 00:56:25.620
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:56:25.620 --> 00:56:28.810
PROFESSOR: Yeah, it's
maybe 30 microns.

00:56:28.810 --> 00:56:42.420
So there's this idea
that a cell might

00:56:42.420 --> 00:56:45.170
go like this for 30 microns.

00:56:45.170 --> 00:56:47.740
And it takes about a
second for it to do that.

00:56:47.740 --> 00:56:50.810
But then that's a run.

00:56:50.810 --> 00:56:53.730
But then it'll engage in
some random tumble that

00:56:53.730 --> 00:56:56.840
leads it to go some
other direction, and then

00:56:56.840 --> 00:56:59.730
another tumble, and then it kind
of goes a different direction,

00:56:59.730 --> 00:57:02.210
and so forth.

00:57:02.210 --> 00:57:04.345
So these are runs and tumbles.

00:57:10.650 --> 00:57:12.760
Now, the nice thing
here is that you

00:57:12.760 --> 00:57:16.850
can see that to measure this
concentration over here,

00:57:16.850 --> 00:57:19.880
the change of concentration
across the cell

00:57:19.880 --> 00:57:22.860
went as a, which might only be
1 or 2 microns, whereas here

00:57:22.860 --> 00:57:25.910
now the E. coli can measure
a change in a concentration

00:57:25.910 --> 00:57:28.170
over tens of microns.

00:57:28.170 --> 00:57:31.330
So it's in some ways like a
longer antenna that allows it

00:57:31.330 --> 00:57:32.650
to pick up the signal better.

00:57:36.910 --> 00:57:40.580
There's a comment
about what happens here

00:57:40.580 --> 00:57:45.790
in the sense that if you
imagine you have a cell,

00:57:45.790 --> 00:57:51.290
it's a few microns in size,
flagella is pushing it,

00:57:51.290 --> 00:57:56.140
it's going at 30
microns per second.

00:57:56.140 --> 00:57:59.420
The question is,
if at some time it

00:57:59.420 --> 00:58:05.537
stops spinning its flagellum,
how far will it coast?

00:58:16.540 --> 00:58:18.400
And this is after
stopping swimming.

00:58:26.300 --> 00:58:32.653
OK, so we'll do an approximate,
so 10 micron maybe.

00:58:51.040 --> 00:58:55.146
How many microns does a cell
coast after it stops swimming?

00:58:55.146 --> 00:58:57.020
AUDIENCE: This is
a bacterial cell?

00:58:57.020 --> 00:58:58.720
PROFESSOR: This is
a bacterial cell.

00:58:58.720 --> 00:59:04.060
This is E. coli, and this is,
we'll say, 3 microns in size.

00:59:09.830 --> 00:59:15.290
Ready-- three, two, one.

00:59:15.290 --> 00:59:18.790
All right, OK, so everybody
says-- and is this actually the

00:59:18.790 --> 00:59:19.619
right answer?

00:59:19.619 --> 00:59:20.160
AUDIENCE: No.

00:59:20.160 --> 00:59:22.450
PROFESSOR: No, it's not.

00:59:22.450 --> 00:59:24.710
So this is the
closest, it's true.

00:59:24.710 --> 00:59:26.450
But none of these
things are true.

00:59:26.450 --> 00:59:28.546
So how far does it coast?

00:59:28.546 --> 00:59:30.300
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:59:30.300 --> 00:59:35.240
PROFESSOR: Right, yeah, so
it's some ridiculous-- I mean,

00:59:35.240 --> 00:59:38.450
and this is really,
really weird.

00:59:38.450 --> 00:59:41.660
This guy-- 30 microns a second.

00:59:41.660 --> 00:59:44.980
So this is 10 times its
body length every second.

00:59:44.980 --> 00:59:47.710
It's really shooting along.

00:59:47.710 --> 00:59:51.610
But the moment that it stops
swimming, it stops moving.

00:59:51.610 --> 00:59:54.090
So it's none of these things.

00:59:54.090 --> 00:59:57.350
It was 1 angstrom or
less than an angstrom?

00:59:57.350 --> 00:59:58.770
AUDIENCE: 0.1.

00:59:58.770 --> 01:00:04.180
PROFESSOR: OK, 0.1
angstroms, which this is

01:00:04.180 --> 01:00:05.688
10 to the minus five microns.

01:00:11.430 --> 01:00:13.800
OK, so it's orders
of magnitude smaller

01:00:13.800 --> 01:00:15.590
than you would ever imagine.

01:00:15.590 --> 01:00:19.600
And that's because our intuition
comes from kind of our length

01:00:19.600 --> 01:00:24.090
scales where if I were
swimming this fast,

01:00:24.090 --> 01:00:27.070
I would keep on drifting
after I stopped swimming.

01:00:27.070 --> 01:00:30.410
But that's not the world
that bacteria live in.

01:00:30.410 --> 01:00:32.846
And that's because of
the low Reynolds number.

01:00:38.830 --> 01:00:41.990
The Reynolds number is
much, much less than 1.

01:00:41.990 --> 01:00:43.900
So this thing is the
dimensionless number

01:00:43.900 --> 01:00:47.410
that quantifies the relative
importance of inertial forces

01:00:47.410 --> 01:00:48.400
to viscous forces.

01:00:51.200 --> 01:00:54.070
Now there was some
discussion of the Reynolds

01:00:54.070 --> 01:00:56.830
number in your reading.

01:00:56.830 --> 01:01:00.780
I maybe won't get into
too much detail about it.

01:01:00.780 --> 01:01:02.890
But what I'll say
is that if anybody

01:01:02.890 --> 01:01:05.370
wants to talk about a way of
thinking about the Reynolds

01:01:05.370 --> 01:01:07.310
number, maybe you can
ask me after class,

01:01:07.310 --> 01:01:12.670
and I can explain to you why
this weird expression can

01:01:12.670 --> 01:01:18.160
be thought of as the ratio of
the inertial to viscous forces.

01:01:18.160 --> 01:01:23.410
But I want to think
a little bit more

01:01:23.410 --> 01:01:26.070
about the strategy that
these cells are following,

01:01:26.070 --> 01:01:33.780
which is, why is it that a
run is of the length scale

01:01:33.780 --> 01:01:35.300
that it is?

01:01:35.300 --> 01:01:39.710
In particular, why
not go further?

01:01:39.710 --> 01:01:44.110
We already said that its
ability to measure concentration

01:01:44.110 --> 01:01:47.570
is somehow-- if you did
a direct measurement,

01:01:47.570 --> 01:01:49.670
it would scale with
the size of the cell.

01:01:49.670 --> 01:01:53.300
In this case, it sort of scales
like the length of the run.

01:01:53.300 --> 01:01:56.680
So why not run for
10 times longer,

01:01:56.680 --> 01:01:59.930
100 times longer, so you can
get a really good measurement

01:01:59.930 --> 01:02:02.430
of a gradient?

01:02:02.430 --> 01:02:04.430
AUDIENCE: Because if
you're going the wrong way,

01:02:04.430 --> 01:02:06.384
then you'd go 10 times longer.

01:02:06.384 --> 01:02:07.800
PROFESSOR: OK, so
it could be just

01:02:07.800 --> 01:02:08.780
if you're going the wrong way.

01:02:08.780 --> 01:02:10.154
Although then we
could maybe even

01:02:10.154 --> 01:02:12.462
be just more sensitive in that.

01:02:12.462 --> 01:02:14.170
Because what's striking
is that even when

01:02:14.170 --> 01:02:17.460
it's going in the right
direction, it still tumbles.

01:02:17.460 --> 01:02:20.170
The difference between
the run lengths

01:02:20.170 --> 01:02:23.120
and the correct and incorrect
directions are kind of modest,

01:02:23.120 --> 01:02:23.900
I guess.

01:02:23.900 --> 01:02:26.290
So maybe we could come up
with a different strategy

01:02:26.290 --> 01:02:27.748
where we say, all
right, well, if I

01:02:27.748 --> 01:02:30.160
feel like things are getting
worse, I'll tumble quickly.

01:02:30.160 --> 01:02:31.910
But if I feel like
things are going great,

01:02:31.910 --> 01:02:35.667
maybe then I'll go in
the same direction,

01:02:35.667 --> 01:02:37.500
and I'll measure that
gradient really finely

01:02:37.500 --> 01:02:39.522
so I can get precisely
the right direction.

01:02:39.522 --> 01:02:41.680
So I guess the
question is, is there

01:02:41.680 --> 01:02:44.690
anything that's going
to limit how useful it

01:02:44.690 --> 01:02:51.680
is to go swimming, even in a
good direction, in principle?

01:02:51.680 --> 01:02:52.648
Yeah.

01:02:52.648 --> 01:02:57.488
AUDIENCE: So it's so small that
collision with actual molecules

01:02:57.488 --> 01:02:59.908
can randomize its
direction as it goes along,

01:02:59.908 --> 01:03:02.640
and it sort of loses memory.

01:03:02.640 --> 01:03:05.730
PROFESSOR: And this is a weird
thing, that not only does

01:03:05.730 --> 01:03:10.180
diffusion act kind of in a
linear sense on the center

01:03:10.180 --> 01:03:12.540
of mass position of
an object, but it also

01:03:12.540 --> 01:03:17.180
acts rotationally, which means
that the cell and other objects

01:03:17.180 --> 01:03:22.910
in liquid lose their
orientational order.

01:03:22.910 --> 01:03:24.730
What that means is that
if this cell starts

01:03:24.730 --> 01:03:26.484
swimming in one
direction, it's actually

01:03:26.484 --> 01:03:27.900
the case that after
a few seconds,

01:03:27.900 --> 01:03:30.200
it forgets where it was going.

